  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div xml:id="KT50-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">kiḻavaṟkup pāṅkāyiṉa vāyilkaṭkuk kiḻatti colliyatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Spoken by HER to the mediators who were close to HIM.</p>
          </div>



        <div xml:id="KT50">
            <lg type="edition">
<l>                aiyavi yaṉṉa ciṟuvī ñāḻal</l>
<l>                cevvī marutiṉ cemmaloṭu tāayt</l>
<l>                tuṟaiyaṇin taṉṟava rūrē yiṟaiyiṟan</l>
<l>                tilaṅkuvaḷai nekiḻac cāayp</l>
<l>                pulampaṇin taṉṟavar maṇanta tōḷē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
             <l>Like white mustard the small-blossomed Ñāḻal</l>
             <l rend="indent">spread together with withered red Arjuna blossoms</l>
             <l>adorned<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">aṇintaṉṟu</term>: here another clear example for the aspectual character of the "preterite". The nuance is not to be found in a retrospective, but rather in the fact that the blossoms have already fallen and the loneliness has been put on as an ornament.</note> the ghat in his village.</l>
             <l rend="indent4">Wasted away</l>
             <l rend="indent">so that the shining bangles become loose [and] slip over the joints,<note place="foot">A smaller syntactical problem here is the absolutive <term xml:lang="ta">iṟantu</term>. One would expect either infinitive (as in the above translation) or a different sequence: bangles first become loose and only then slip down.</note></l>
             <l>the arms he clung to are adorned by loneliness.</l>


                </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
  </text>
